Happay Integration Playbook

 

Standard Operating Procedures for Seamless Enterprise Integration

1. Overview

The Happay Integration document is a centralized technical and functional guide for integrating third-party enterprise systems with the Happay platform. It is designed to support implementation teams, system integrators, and enterprise IT stakeholders throughout the integration lifecycle  from planning and design to deployment and support. This documentation ensures consistency, clarity, and completeness in how integrations are configured, tested, and maintained, enabling seamless synchronization of data across the enterprise ecosystem.

2. Purpose

To provide standardized, step-by-step instructions, payload references, encryption protocols, authentication formats, error handling techniques, and configuration templates for all supported integrations. It ensures that every client and internal team member is aligned with Happay's best practices for secure, scalable, and flexible integrations.

3. Covered Integrations

  • Single Sign-On (SSO)  SAML 2.0 based identity federation
  • HRMS Integration  API and SFTP-based employee data sync
  • HRMS Customization  Secure exchange via AES/PGP encryption
  • Accounting Forward Integration  Expense export to ERPs
  • Accounting Reverse Integration  ERP confirmations back to Happay

4. Intended Audience

  • Enterprise Clients
  • Client-Side IT Admins
  • Implementation & Configuration Teams
  • Solution Architects
  • Integration Consultants
  • QA & Support Engineers

5. Single Sign-On (SSO)

Objective

The objective of this document is to define the standardized process for integrating Single Sign-On (SSO) functionality with the Happay platform using SAML 2.0-compliant Identity Providers (IdPs). It aims to ensure a seamless, secure, and centralized authentication experience for users while simplifying access management for IT administrators. This document serves as a comprehensive guide for both internal teams (Product, Support, Engineering) and external stakeholders (Client IT Admins) involved in implementing SSO.

Scope

This document covers the entire lifecycle of SSO setup and integration with Happay, including but not limited to:

  • Overview of supported SSO protocols and compatible Identity Providers.
  • Configuration responsibilities for both Happay and the client-side IdP.
  • Key parameters and attributes required for successful SSO communication.
  • Metadata exchange and attribute mapping standards.
  • Error troubleshooting and common FAQs related to SSO authentication.
  • Specific configuration documentation for Azure AD, OneLogin, and Google Workspace.

This document is applicable for enterprise clients who require identity federation using SAML 2.0 for enhanced security and centralized identity control. It does not cover OAuth, OpenID Connect, or other authentication mechanisms.

Definitions

  • SSO (Single Sign-On): A user authentication process that permits a user to enter one set of login credentials (e.g., name and password) to access multiple applications.
  • IdP (Identity Provider): The service or platform (e.g., Azure AD, Okta, Google Workspace) that authenticates users and provides identity information to Happay.
  • SP (Service Provider): In this context, Happay acts as the Service Provider that receives authentication assertions from the IdP.
  • SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language): An open standard for exchanging authentication and authorization data between parties, particularly between an IdP and a Service Provider.
  • ACS (Assertion Consumer Service) URL: The endpoint on Happay where SAML assertions from the IdP are posted after a successful authentication.
  • Entity ID (SP Identifier): A unique string used to identify the Happay service provider configuration within the IdP.
  • Attribute Mapping: The process of linking user information fields from the IdP to the corresponding fields expected by Happay.
  • X.509 Certificate: A digital certificate used to verify the identity of the IdP and establish a secure communication channel.

Single Sign-On

Single Sign-On (SSO) configuration for Happay allows users to log in to the Happay platform using their organizations identity provider (IdP), such as Azure AD, Okta, Google Workspace, or any SAML 2.0-compliant IdP. This ensures secure and seamless user access while centralizing authentication.

FAQs

1.    Why do I get a User Identifier Not Found error when logging in via SSO?

This error usually indicates that the attribute mapping from your Identity Provider (IdP) to Happay is not correct, even after all configurations are done. Please make sure your attribute mapping matches exactly as below (case sensitive):

Attribute Name

Attribute Type

User.email

user.mail

NameID

user.mail

2.    Why do I get a User Identifier Not Found error when logging in via SSO, even if the attribute mapping looks correct?

If attribute mapping appears correct but the error persists, then inspect the actual SAML response to verify the exact details sent by the you to Happay are same or not like certificate, attributes etc.

3.    Is there a way for the direct redirection to the IdP page?

Yes, using the below ACS link, we can directly access the IdP page.

https://expense.happay.in/login/sso?domain_name=<>

4.    Why am I getting this error as shown below, while trying to login via SSO?

This is typically because of the SSO being disabled from Happays end in the v-ops dashboard. Once we enable it, the client wont face this issue

6. HRMS Integration

Objective

The objective of this document is to provide a comprehensive framework for integrating an organization's Human Resource Management System (HRMS) with the Happay platform. This integration ensures seamless, secure, and automated synchronization of employee dataincluding basic demographic information, job roles, reporting structures, and moreinto Happays expense management ecosystem.

Key goals include:

  • Enabling real-time or scheduled employee data synchronization.
  • Reducing manual data entry and associated errors.
  • Enhancing administrative efficiency and data governance.
  • Supporting compliance with internal policies and external regulations.
  • Providing clarity on integration methods: API-based and SFTP-based.

Scope

This document applies to:

  • HR and IT Teams responsible for implementing and managing HRMS integrations with Happay.
  • System Integrators or Technology Partners who assist in API or SFTP configuration.
  • End Users indirectly benefiting from streamlined onboarding and expense reporting workflows.

It covers:

  • Technical requirements and pre-requisites for integration.
  • Detailed workflows for both API and SFTP-based methods.
  • Field mapping and data formatting standards.
  • IP whitelisting, authentication, and security best practices.
  • Common challenges and error handling protocols.
  • Applicable limitations such as data volume thresholds and update frequencies.

The document is relevant regardless of the HRMS vendor (e.g., Darwinbox, SAP, Workday, Keka), assuming either API or SFTP capabilities exist.

Definition

  • Human Resource Management System (HRMS):
    An HRMS is a software application used by organizations to manage employee information, payroll, recruitment, attendance, and related HR functions. In the context of this integration, the HRMS serves as the source of truth for employee records.
  • HRMS-Happay Integration:
    This refers to the process of enabling a secure and structured flow of employee data from an organizations HRMS into the Happay expense management system. The integration ensures that users on Happay reflect the most recent and accurate employee profiles, facilitating better workflow automation, approval routing, and compliance.
  • API-Based Integration:
    A real-time, secure, and scalable integration method leveraging REST APIs to create, update, or deactivate users in Happay dynamically based on changes in the HRMS.
  • SFTP-Based Integration:
    A file-transfer based approach where structured employee data (typically in CSV format) is periodically uploaded to a secure SFTP server. Happay accesses this server on a scheduled basis to ingest and process the data.
  • Metafields:
    Custom-defined data fields that extend standard employee attributes (e.g., location code, cost center, employment type) used for personalized configurations and reporting within Happay.
  • NativeFields:
    These are the essential details required to create an employee profile in Happay. Without this information, an employees data or profile cannot be generated.


HRMS

Happay HRMS integration is the process of connecting your company's HR management system (HRMS) with Happay's expense management platform. It ensures that employee data like name, ID, email, department, role, and reporting manager is automatically synced into Happay.

NOTE: Before kick starting the HRMS integration, ask Blueprint file from the AM, which contains the Fields.

Types of HRMS Integration with Happay

Happay supports two main types of HRMS integration:

1.    SFTP-Based Integration (File Transfer):

  • Data is exported from HRMS as CSV/Excel files.
  • Files are uploaded to a secure SFTP server.
  • Happay fetches files on a scheduled basis (e.g., daily).
  • Suitable for systems with no API support.
  • Easy to set up and maintain.
  • Not real-time; updates occur at set intervals.
  • Best for basic, periodic sync needs.

2.    API-Based Integration:

  • Real-time or near real-time data sync using APIs.
  • Secure connection between HRMS and Happay via HTTPS.
  • Supports employee creation, updates, and deactivation dynamically.
  • Ideal for modern HRMS platforms (e.g., Darwinbox, Keka, SAP, Workday).
  • Provides detailed error logs and better monitoring.
  • Requires development effort and technical setup.
  • Highly scalable and flexible for growing organizations.


Step-by-Step Guide to HRMS Integration with Happay: SFTP Approach

1.    Customer Uses Their Own SFTP Server:

o   The organization (customer) sets up and maintains the SFTP server where files will be uploaded.

2.    Whitelist Happays IP Addresses:

o   Happay shares its static IP addresses of its SFTP server.

o   The customer whitelists these IPs to allow secure access to their SFTP server.

3.    Share Structured CSV Format:

o   The customer and Happay agree on a common CSV template for employee data.

o   The preferred delimiter for the CSV file is PIPE (|). 

o   Typical fields include:

§  First Name

§  Last Name

§  Email ID

§  Mobile Number

§  Mobile Extension

§  Gender

§  Date of Birth (DOB)

§  Title (Salutation)

§  Along with the metafields which the customer decides.

4.    Customer Shares Test File:

o   A sample CSV file following the agreed format is uploaded to the SFTP.

5.    Happay Conducts SFTP Connection Testing:

o   Happay tests connectivity to the customers SFTP server.

o   Verifies folder path access, credentials, file visibility, and validates the sample file structure.

o   Using this CSV file structure, we create a lambda function and map the fields at the code level, post the SFTP connection testing is done.

6.    Customer Begins Regular File Uploads:

o   Once testing is successful, the customer starts placing updated CSV files at predefined intervals (daily/weekly).

7.    Happay Starts Scheduled File Processing:

o   Happay sets up a scheduled job to pull and process the uploaded files.

o   Employee records are created, updated, or deactivated in Happay as per the file content.

NOTE: To ensure optimal performance and stability, we recommend that customers inform us of the approximate volume of employee records they intend to send. As a reference, the Happay platform comfortably supports up to 20,000 records per file, especially when the dataset includes a larger number of columns.

Step-by-Step Guide to HRMS Integration with Happay: API Approach

1.    Customer Opts for API-Based Integration:

  • The organization decides to integrate their HRMS with Happay using APIs.
  • This requires basic development capability on the customers side.

2.    Happay Shares API Documentation & Payload Structure:

  • Happay provides:
    • API base URL - https://api-v2.happay.in/auth/v1/add_update_user/
    • Authentication mechanism (usually Bearer Token)
    • Detailed API documentation
    • Sample payload structure with mandatory fields like:
      • First Name
      • Last Name
      • Email ID
      • Mobile Number
      • Mobile Extension
      • Gender
      • Date of Birth (DOB)
      • Along with the metafields which the customer wants.

3.    Customer Develops Integration at Their End:

  • The customers technical team builds the logic to push employee data to Happay using the provided API specs.
  • This may include new user creation, profile updates, and deactivation.

4.    Happay Whitelists Customer's IP Addresses:

  • Customer shares their source server IPs.
  • Happay whitelists them for secure API traffic.

5.    Testing & UAT:

  • API calls are first tested in a staging/sandbox environment.
  • Happay validates payload structure, data mapping, error handling, and response codes.

FAQs

API Integration:

1.    How many employee records can we send per API call?

Typically, one employee record per API call is recommended for better tracking and error handling.

2.    When to pass the last working day?

The Last Working Day field can be passed at any time. It is flexible and can be updated as neededeven after the user has been created.

3.    Is data pushed via API visible in real-time?

Yes, employee data pushed through the API is reflected in Happay in real-time, ensuring immediate visibility and availability within the platform.

4.    Can we update a user's information (like mobile number or manager) later via API?

Yes, the API supports updates to existing records at any time.

5.    Do we need to whitelist our IPs for API access?

Yes, IP whitelisting is mandatory. Happay will only accept requests from registered IP addresses for security reasons.

SFTP Integration

1. Who hosts the SFTP server  the customer or Happay?

In most setups, the customer hosts the SFTP server, and Happay connects to it after IP whitelisting.

2. How often can we place files on the SFTP server?

Files can be placed daily, weekly, or at any preferred interval as agreed during setup.

3. What format should the file be in?

The file must be in a pre-approved CSV format, containing fields like First Name, Last Name, Email ID, Mobile Number, Gender, DOB, etc.

Error Handling:

1. How do I know if an API call failed?

The API will return an HTTP error status (e.g., 400, 401, 409) along with a descriptive message explaining what went wrong (e.g., missing email, invalid format). We can also distribute the logs via email directly through Metabase.

2. Why do we receive the error "An active or deactivated account already exists with the same Email ID" during API user creation or update?

 This error occurs when an employee record with the same email ID already exists in Happayeither as active or previously deactivated. The system prevents duplicate email IDs to maintain data integrity.

3. What does Manager ID or Email not found indicate?

This error means the reporting manager or approver specified for the employee does not exist in Happay. Ensure the manager is onboarded and active before linking them.

 

7. HRMS Integration  Customization

Objective

This document outlines the supported customizations for integrating with third-party Human Resource Management Systems (HRMS) via API or SFTP. It focuses specifically on encryption mechanisms to ensure secure data exchange.

Integration Methods

1.    API-Based Integration

API-based integration is used for real-time or near real-time synchronization between the HRMS and our systems.

1.1.        Supported Encryption Mechanisms:

  • AES-256:

Payloads are encrypted using a shared secret key.

We decrypt incoming requests and send back encrypted responses.

  • PGP (Pretty Good Privacy):

Clients encrypt requests using our public key.

We decrypt requests and send responses as plain JSON.

1.2.             Step-by-Step Process:

1.2.1.     What the Client Needs to Do:

1.  Tell us whether they want to use AES-256 or PGP.

2.  Share:

o   API documentation

o   Data formats (request and response)

o   Pre-shared key (if AES-256) or their PGP public key (if using PGP)

1.2.2.     What Happay Will Do:

1.  Share our PGP public key (if needed).

2.  Set up the logic to decrypt incoming requests and prepare responses.

3.  Connect with the clients API.

4.  Test the full flow to ensure data is correctly encrypted and decrypted.

2.     SFTP-Based Integration

SFTP integration is used for sending and receiving data in files, typically on a scheduled basis.

2.1.         Supported Encryption Mechanisms:

  • Only PGP is supported for file encryption.

2.2.         Step-by-Step Process:

2.2.1.    What the Client Needs to Do:

1.  Share:

o   File format and sample data

o   How often files will be sent

o   Their PGP public key

1.  Encrypt each file with our PGP public key before uploading to SFTP.

2.2.2.    What Happay Will Do:

1.  Share our PGP public key.

2.  Set up SFTP folder and access.

3.  Decrypt files automatically when received.

4.  Test with a few files to ensure everything works as expected.

 

 

8. Accounting Forward


Objective

To establish a standardized procedure for forwarding transaction and report data from the Happay platform to the organization's accounting/ERP systems (e.g., SAP, Oracle). This ensures timely and accurate expense recognition and reconciliation.

Scope

This SOP applies to all employees involved in the accounting integration, expense tracking, and ERP reconciliation processes using Happay's APIs or SFTP-based interfaces.

Definitions

  • Accounting Forward: Automated or semi-automated process of sending expense data to an ERP system once it reaches a defined status.
  • ERP: Enterprise Resource Planning system (e.g., SAP, Oracle, Tally, NetSuite, Microsoft Dynamics)
  • Transaction: A single expense item created in Happay (e.g., advance, ticket booking)
  • Report: A bundle of transactions submitted for reimbursement or approval.

Supported ERP Systems

Happay supports seamless integration with the following ERP systems:

  • SAP (including SAP S/4HANA)
  • Oracle Financials / NetSuite
  • Tally ERP
  • Microsoft Dynamics 365 (Business Central / Finance & Operations)
  • QuickBooks Online & Desktop
  • Zoho Books
  • Custom ERP platforms via API or SFTP integration

Integration can be real-time (via APIs) or periodic (via SFTP) depending on client preferences and ERP capabilities.

Supported API Authentication methods

  • Basic Authentication (user name, password)
  • Bearer Token (generated at client end)
  • x-api-key,
  • OAuth 2.0

Integration Interfaces

1.    API-Based Integration

Happay provides flexibility in how API-based integration is implemented, depending on whether the client requires a standard or customized payload.

1.1.         Standard Payload: If the client's employee data structure aligns with Happays standard payload format, the integration process is streamlined.   • Notify Happay in case of file ingestion failures

2.2.2.    Happay:

  • Configure SFTP path and credentials on the frontend
  • Generate and deliver files in the agreed format
  • Ensure timely upload as per defined schedule
  • Provide ongoing support and file delivery assurance

Flow Description

1.    Start:User submits a report or an advance; it enters the workflow.

2.    Approval/Verification:Once the advance or report is approved, it is triggered to the ERP API.

3.    Authentication Check:

o   If authentication fails, the trigger is rejected.

o   If successful, data is forwarded to the ERP system.

4.    ERP Response:

o   If ERP posting is successful, the posting details are updated through reverse integration.

o   If it fails due to functional issues at the ERP, it must be retriggered from the frontend.

 

 

9. Accounting Reverse

Objective

To outline the standard process of reverse integration (accounting reverse) in Happay, where ERP systems send back posting confirmation and relevant metadata to update the status of reports and transactions within the Happay system.

Scope

This document applies to all customers and teams involved in real-time and semi-automated (SFTP) accounting forward integrations, where ERP acknowledgment is required to complete the lifecycle of expense reports and transactions.

Definitions

  • Accounting Reverse: The process of receiving status updates and posting confirmations from ERP systems into Happay, after a successful forward integration.
  • ERP: The client's Enterprise Resource Planning system (SAP, Oracle, Tally, NetSuite, etc.).
  • Reverse Payload: The data structure received from the ERP containing posting information.

Supported ERP Systems

Happay supports seamless integration with the following ERP systems:

  • SAP (including SAP S/4HANA)
  • Oracle Financials / NetSuite
  • Tally ERP
  • Microsoft Dynamics 365 (Business Central / Finance & Operations)
  • QuickBooks Online & Desktop
  • Zoho Books
  • Custom ERP platforms via API or SFTP integration

Integration can be real-time (via APIs) or periodic (via SFTP) depending on client preferences and ERP capabilities.

Integration Interfaces

1.    API Reverse Integration

  • In this method, the client's ERP system directly calls Happay's exposed API endpoint to confirm posting of transactions or reports.

1.1.        API Endpoint

METHOD: POST 

URL: https://api-v2.happay.in/auth/v1/updateobjectstatus/

1.2.        Required Parameters

 

1.3.          Sample Request

{

    "requestId": "POST78901",

    "objectId": "HPRPL2025060812345678HP",

    "objectType": ""Reports" or "Transaction"",

    "metaFields": {

        "ERPPostRef": "SAP_DOC_2210",

        "PostingDate": "2025-06-09"

    }

}

1.4.         Sample Response

{

    "res_code": "0",

    "res_str": "Object Updated Successfully",

    "res_det": {

        "objectId": "HPRPL2025060812345678HP",

        "objectType": ""Reports" or "Transaction""

    }

}

1.5.        Roles & Responsibilities

1.5.1.      Client:

  • Call Happay's API endpoint /auth/v1/updateobjectstatus/ after posting data in ERP.
  • Ensure proper object ID, metadata, and authentication.

1.5.2.         Happay:

  • Expose and secure the updateobjectstatus API.
  • Validate request structure and apply updates.
  • Log reverse update activity for audits.

2.    Reverse Integration via SFTP (Scheduled Processing)

In this method, clients place ERP posting confirmation files into an SFTP folder. Happay processes these files periodically to update object status.

2.1.             Process Steps

  • Client places the file in a pre-configured SFTP folder.
  • Happay AWS Lambda service picks and parses the file.
  • Lambda maps the ERP fields to Happay's structure.
  • Happay internally calls the same updateobjectstatus API through the lambda code to apply updates.

2.2. Required Fields in SFTP File

  • requestId
  • objectId
  • objectType
  • any metafields that client requires.

2.3. Responsibilities

     2.3.1. Client:

  • Place files with correct data into the SFTP folder.
  • Maintain file structure as agreed during onboarding.

     2.3.2. Happay:

  • Configure SFTP polling and schedule.
  • Build and deploy AWS Lambda for parsing and transformation.
  • Call updateobjectstatus internally to complete reverse update.
  • Maintain logs and send failure alerts where needed.
  • Client shares ERP posting confirmations in a file format
  • Happay polling service retrieves the file from the SFTP folder
  • The file is parsed and matching objects in Happay are updated

Reverse Integration Workflow

The reverse integration process involves updating Happay with ERP posting confirmation data, enabling visibility and traceability. Below is a bifurcation of the flow for both API-based and SFTP-based reverse integration methods:

1.           API-Based Reverse Integration Flow

  • Report/Transaction is submitted and forwarded to ERP.
  • ERP system posts the data successfully.
  • ERP system makes a real-time API call to Happay's updateobjectstatus endpoint.
  • The API includes metadata such as ERP Reference Number, Posting Date, etc.
  • Happay updates the report/transaction status to "Posted" and stores metadata.
  • Users can view posting confirmation inside Happay UI.

2.           SFTP-Based Reverse Integration Flow

  • Report/Transaction is submitted and forwarded to ERP.
  • ERP system posts the data successfully.
  • ERP places a file with posting confirmation in the pre-configured SFTP folder.
  • AWS Lambda (configured by Happay) picks up the file.
  • Lambda transforms and maps data fields as per Happay's format.
  • Lambda calls the updateobjectstatus API internally.
  • Happay updates the object status and stores the ERP metadata.
  • Posting status is reflected inside the Happay platform for end users.

 

 

10. Budget Check

Objective

To define a standardized and scalable process for integrating client-managed budget validation with the Happay platform. This specification ensures that every transaction initiated within Happay (such as travel requests or report submissions) is checked against the client's real-time budget data. It lays out the technical frameworkincluding API payload structure, communication flow, and decision routingso that organizations can enforce budgetary controls directly from their ERP or financial systems. The objective is to provide transparency, compliance, and flexibility while maintaining a seamless user experience on the Happay interface.

Definitions

·       Budget Check: The process of validating if sufficient funds are available for a transaction based on specific criteria such as WBS Code, Cost Center, and Project Code.

·        Budget Status: The outcome of the budget check, typically expressed as SUCCESS or FAILURE, indicating whether the requested amount is within the available budget.

·        Available Budget: The remaining amount under a specified WBS, Cost Center, or Project that can be used for new transactions.

·        Reference ID: A unique identifier for the transaction request sent from Happay to the clients system.

·        Auto Container Action: A middleware-triggered mechanism that auto-advances a request in Happay workflow upon successful budget validation.

Scope

This document applies to all clients integrating their internal budgeting systems with the Happay platform for travel and report-level expense validation.

It includes:

·        The expected API format and payload specifications for budget validation.

·        Client and Happay responsibilities in the validation flow.

·        Communication protocol and timeout handling.

·        Real-time response handling, field mapping, and workflow routing.

Responsibilities Breakdown

Happay Will:

  • Send transaction details to the clients REST API.
  • Ensure secure API authentication.
  • Capture the response and update internal request status.
  • Trigger next-step automation (e.g., Auto Container Action).

Client Must:

  • Provide a secure REST API (POST + JSON payload).
  • Perform budget validation via ERP/third-party system.
  • Respond with status and available budget in JSON.
  • Apply any internal business logic before responding.

Integration Type

In Happay, budget check is supported only via API integration. Clients are required to expose a REST API that accepts a JSON-formatted payload. This allows Happay to perform real-time, structured budget validations during transaction workflows.

Supported Features by Happay

·        Outbound REST API invocation from Happay to client endpoint

·        JSON-based request body structure

·        Flexible request payload mapped to WBS, Cost Center, Project Code, etc.

·        Configurable per-transaction type (e.g., TRAVEL, REPORT)

·        Header-based authentication: Bearer token, Basic Auth, or IP whitelisting

·        Middleware support for automated action routing (e.g., Auto Container Action)

·        Field mapping and dynamic metafield population using response data

Client to Happay Response Format

The client can define its own response format; however, Happay recommends including the following metafields in the response for consistent processing and reporting:

·        availableBudget

·        budgetStatus

These fields are used to update the request status and are necessary for downstream workflow and reporting purposes.

On success sample response payload:

{

  "status": "SUCCESS",

  "message": "Budget is available",

  "availableAmount": 75000,

  "currency": "INR",

  "validationCode": "OK-200"

}

 

On failure sample response payload:

{

  "status": "FAILURE",

  "message": "Budget exceeded for WBS WBS00123",

  "availableAmount": 10000,

  "requestedAmount": 25000,

  "validationCode": "NOK - 400"

}

 

Workflow: Budget Validation

1.     User submits a travel or report request in Happay.

2.    Happay sends transaction data to the clients API endpoint, along with identifiers like WBS code, cost center, project code, and transaction type.

3.    Clients ERP or third-party budgeting system receives the request and performs validation:

·        Checks for available budget against the requested amount.

·        May optionally route the request through internal approvals or thresholds.

4.    The client responds with:

·        Budget status (SUCCESS or FAILURE)

·        Available amount

·        Any validation message or error code

5.    Happay receives the response and:

·        Updates the report/travel request using updateStatus API.

·        Stores key fields like availableBudget and budgetStatus in the requests metafields.

6.    Workflow Routing:

NOTE: The workflow and auto action depend on the client requirement. This is just for sample.

·        If budget is available:

§  The request status becomes PENDING or moves to the next stage based on workflow.

§  If middleware is enabled for auto-routing, the system triggers Auto Container Action.

·        If budget is not available:

§  Action depends on client configuration:

§  Travel: A new travel request may need to be initiated.

§  Report: The user may be allowed to resubmit the report after adjustments.

7.    Validation Scope:

o   Travel: Only for online flight and hotels bookings (domestic/international), not applicable for offline bookings.

o   Report: Validation level depends on where the budget check is configured in the clients workflow (start/mid/end).

NOTES

·        Happay does not run any internal logic to approve or reject budget.

·        Happay does not own the API or response logic; all decision-making lies with the client.

·        REST API and JSON format are mandatory for integration.

·        If client doesn't share payload, Happay can propose a standard one.

·        Required response fields for Happay to continue include status, availableBudget, and optionally validationCode.

·        For reverse budgeting or cancellation, metafields are updated using previously saved values.

 

Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)

1.     Can we define our own API payload format?

Yes. While Happay provides a standard JSON payload, clients can define their own format. Happay will adapt as long as key response parameters (e.g., status, availableBudget, budgetStatus) are included.

2.    Do we need to expose a new API for budget check?

Yes. Clients must expose a POST REST API that accepts JSON payloads from Happay for real-time budget validation.

3.    Can we apply approval workflows within our system before responding?

Absolutely. Your ERP or third-party system can include validation rules, thresholds, or approval chains before sending the budget response.

4.    Can we include additional details in the response?

Yes. Fields for example like validation codes, business messages, or thresholds crossed can be included and mapped on Happays interface if needed.

5.    Where does Happay show the budget check result?

The result is updated in the requests metafields and used to determine whether the request proceeds or is flagged.

6.    What kind of transactions are covered by budget check?

Only report and online travel transactions (e.g., flights) are eligible for API-based budget check.

7.    Can we change the validation level per report workflow stage?

Yes. Budget validation can be configured at different stages depending on your workflow logic.

8.    What if we need to reverse budget or handle cancellations?

Happay uses the stored metafields like availableBudget and budgetStatus to reflect reverse budgeting or status resets.

 

11. Travel Management Company

Objective

To define the end-to-end process for integrating Travel Management Company (TMC) invoicing with Happay based on varied client-specific requirements. The integration ensures seamless booking synchronization, automatic expense creation, and reverse invoice reconciliation to maintain transparency and efficiency.

Definitions

  • TMC: Travel management company that manages travel bookings, ticket issuance, and post-travel invoicing.
  • MyBiz: Travel booking platform.
  • SBT (Self-Booking Tool): Allows direct bookings from the platform
  • PNR: Passenger Name Record  a unique booking reference generated by the airline or TMC.
  • Sector: A single leg of a journey between two locations (e.g., Delhi to Mumbai is one sector). Multi-city trips are made up of multiple sectors.
  • JSON Payload: Format for exchanging booking/ticketing data
  • Fulfillment Engine: Updates Happay about booking fulfillment by TMCs
  • Reverse Integration: Structured invoice data pulled from TMCs into Happay
  • TMC: A third-party agency that manages travel bookings, ticket issuance, and post-travel invoicing
  • MyBiz: Happay's travel and expense booking interface
  • SBT (Self-Booking Tool): Allows direct bookings
  • PNR: Passenger Name Record
  • JSON Payload: Format for exchanging booking/ticketing data
  • Fulfillment Engine: Updates Happay about booking fulfillment by TMCs
  • Reverse Integration: Structured invoice data pulled from TMCs into Happay

Scope

This SOP applies to:

·        Clients using Happay for corporate travel.

·        Travel Partners (TMCs) such as ITH, Riya, Thomas Cook, SOTC, FCM, Elix, Train, SKH, Hummingbird, B2T.

·        Happays integration and implementation teams.

·        System Integrators involved in API/SFTP configuration.

It Covers:

·        Booking to ticketing to invoicing flow.

·        Expense line item creation.

·        TMC invoice ingestion and reconciliation.

·        Client-specific field configuration.

6.    Security & Compliance

o   Secure storage and handling of employee booking data.

TMC Booking & Payload Handling Scenarios

This section explains how Happay handles different travel booking patterns from both a data and business logic perspective. Each scenario includes real-world airline examples, payload handling rules, and specific notes about PNR, ticketing, and integration.

1. Single Journey  Single Passenger

Example: One-way flight from Delhi to Mumbai for a single employee.

  • A unique Trip ID is generated.
  • JSON payload includes one segment and one passenger.
  • This payload is pushed to the respective TMC.
  • Upon booking confirmation, the TMC sends the reverse payload via the Create Transaction API.
  • Happay creates an expense line item using the employee ID and trip ID.
  • Note: If 3 employees are traveling, 3 separate payloads and expense entries are created.

2. Domestic Round Trip  Single Passenger

Example: Mumbai to Bangalore and return.

  • Considered two one-way bookings but uses a single Trip ID.
  • PNR behaviour:
    • Air India/Vistara: Same PNR, different ticket numbers for each leg.
    • LCCs (e.g., Indigo, SpiceJet): Different PNRs, but often same ticket numbers.
  • Tax breakup and service charges vary by airline.
  • Happay creates two separate expense line items under one trip.
  • After both legs are booked, TMC returns invoice numbers and reverse payloads for reconciliation.
  • Thomas Cook and Riya send reverse data via Lambda-based Create Transaction APIs.

3. Domestic Multi-City

Example: Hyderabad → Bangalore → Bhopal → Delhi

  • Each flight leg is a separate sector.
  • A single Trip ID is assigned for all legs.
  • The forward payload contains multiple sectors.
  • TMC processes the booking and sends back ticket confirmations per segment.
  • Happay creates individual expense line items for each sector.

4. International Round Trip

Example: Mumbai → Dubai → Mumbai

  • One booking across countries, with one payload and one Trip ID.
  • All flight details, tax components, and passenger information are included.
  • Upon ticketing, TMC responds with a reverse payload and invoice data.
  • Happay matches it to the trip and generates one consolidated expense entry.

5. International Multi-City

Example: Delhi → Tokyo → Hong Kong → Kuala Lumpur

  • Up to 4 sectors are allowed in one payload.
  • If more than 4 sectors are present, Happay splits them into multiple payloads and Trip IDs.
  • PNR behavior:
    • Full-service airlines: One PNR, multiple ticket numbers.
    • LCCs: One PNR per sector.
  • Each payload generates its own ticket and expense line item.
  • GST fields (HSN, SAC) and Corp ID are used if required by client.

6. Connecting Flights

Example: Hyderabad → Bangalore (Indigo) → Mumbai (AirAsia)

  • Treated as a single international-like itinerary.
  • Both legs are included in one payload.
  • pax_type is captured (Adult/Child).
  • total_amount = base fare + taxes + charges
  • TMC returns a single ticket confirmation.
  • Happay reconciles the response and creates one detailed expense entry.

Forward Integration Flow

From employee action (booking) to TMC ticket fulfillment and expense creation in Happay.

Step 1: Employee Initiates Booking via Happay

·        The employee logs into Happay, selects the travel itinerary, and submits a booking request.

·        The system captures:

o   Travel details (origin, destination, dates)

o   Selected carrier or route

o   Estimated fare and employee identifiers

·        Once confirmed, Happay internally tags the booking with a unique Trip ID.

Step 2: Structured Payload Generation

·        A JSON payload is immediately generated containing:

o   trip_id: Internal unique identifier

o   pnr: TMC reservation number

o   employee_id: ID from employee master

o   fare, tax, commission (if applicable)

o   Additional metadata: airline, dates, booking class, etc.

Example:

{

    "trip_id": "TRIP-0001",

    "pnr": "AB12CD",

    "employee_id": "EMP00123",

    "fare": 8000,

    "taxes": 720,

    "commission": 200,

    "total_amount": 8920,

    "booking_date": "2025-07-01",

    "travel_mode": "Flight"

}

 

Step 3: Expense Line Item Auto-Creation in Happay

·        Happay Expense Engine consumes this payload to:

o   Create a debit-side expense line item

o   Associate it with the correct employee and trip ID

o   Mark the booking status as pending fulfillment

This enables:

·        Visibility to finance/auditors that a booking has occurred

·        Downstream reconciliation with the TMCs invoice

Step 4: Payload Transfer to TMC

·        Based on integration type (API/SFTP/offline):

o   If API: Happay system pushes the JSON payload to the TMCs endpoint

o   If Fulfillment Engine (offline): Payload is queued internally; TMC accesses it manually or receives it via periodic sync

Step 5: Ticket Fulfillment by TMC

·        TMC receives the booking request:

o   Books and issues the ticket in their GDS

o   Confirms PNR and updates internal tracking systems

·        If TMC supports real-time API, they send back a ticketing confirmation with:

o   Issued ticket number

o   Fare breakdown

o   PNR + Booking status: Confirmed

Step 6: Handling Offline Bookings (Non-SBT Flow)

·        If the employee books via email or external SBT:

o   The TMC must manually update Happay via the Fulfillment Engine

o   Payload must include:

§  Trip ID

§  Employee ID

§  Fare, taxes, and confirmation details

·        Happay reads this update and manually generates the associated expense line item, tagged to the employee and trip.

Step 7: Booking Cancellation Flow

·        If the employee cancels the booking via Happay:

o   Happay updates the booking status to Cancelled

o   Happay expense line item is also marked cancelled

o   A cancellation alert is sent to the TMC

·        TMC is expected to:

o   Process the cancellation

o   Generate a credit note or cancellation invoice

o   Sync the data back to Happay for reconciliation

If applicable:

·        Refund amounts or cancellation charges are validated

·        Financial records are updated in real time

Reverse Integration Flow

From TMCs invoice generation to Happays validation, reconciliation, and payment readiness.

Step 8: Invoice Generation by TMC

·        After ticket fulfillment:

o   TMC prepares a structured invoice per booking

o   Invoice format can be:

§  CSV/XML over SFTP (client-hosted)

§  Real-time API payload

Each invoice must contain:

·        Trip ID or PNR (as unique identifiers)

·        Fare, tax, commission

·        Invoice number, invoice date

·        Booking status and invoice total

Step 9: Invoice Upload to Happay

·        If via SFTP:

o   TMC places invoice files in a client-hosted SFTP location

o   Happays system is configured to poll or fetch these files periodically

·        If via API:

o   TMC sends the payload directly to Happays reverse-integration endpoint i.e, https://api-v2.happay.in/auth/v1/createtransaction/

·        Method: POST

·        Authentication: Token-based

o   CustomerInfo: ClientId, Username

3.    FCM Travel Specifics

Forward Integration:

FCM integration enables Happay to forward flight booking data for real-time processing via their API. The request is authenticated via an x-api-key header and supports detailed flight and passenger metadata.

                3.1. API Endpoint

·        Booking API URL: https://api.sbt.travel/gemini/trips/create/v1

·        Method: POST

·        Authorization: x-api-key

·        Content-Type: application/json

               3.2. Integration Flow

1.    Happay constructs the JSON payload for each booking request.

2.    Payload is sent to FCM via POST API.

3.    FCM responds with a success message and booking reference.

4.    If any error occurs, FCM sends a structured failure response.

4.    Humming Bird Travel Specifics

Reverse Integration

Humming Birds integration allows direct transaction creation in Happay once bookings are finalized.

            4.1. API Endpoint

·        Production: https://api-v2.happay.in/auth/v1/createtransaction/

·        Method: POST

·        Authentication: Bearer Token (IP whitelisted)

           4.2. Integration Flow

·        Humming Bird sends finalized booking and invoice data directly to Happay.

·        Payload includes base fare, tax, discounts, fees, invoice ID, and optional attachments.

·        Happay validates and maps this data to the employee and trip ID.

·        An expense line item is created in the user's wallet.

FAQs

Q: How does Happay know if a flight is booked?
A: Happay receives the ticketing payload instantly and creates an expense entry to track the booking.

Q: What happens if booking is offline?
A: TMC fulfills the request using Happay's fulfillment engine, allowing expense creation manually.

Q: Can TMC send invoices with commission included?
A: Yes, reverse integration accounts for both base fare and commission.

Q: Are formats fixed across clients?
A: No, field formats are finalized per TMC and client during integration planning.

Q: What is centralized repository?
A: Its a unified view of bookings, invoices, expenses for audit and reconciliation.

 

12. GA Container

Objective

The objective of this document is to define the standardized process for creating and updating GA containers in the Happay platform using API-based integration. These containers capture project-specific metadata fields such as employee assignment, project details, and task information. This helps enable downstream processes like expense control, budgeting, and analytics.

This document serves as a comprehensive guide for both internal teams (Product, Engineering, Support) and client-side stakeholders (IT Admins, Implementation Specialists) to implement GA container APIs correctly.

Scope

This document covers the following:

·        Overview of GA container structure.

·        Responsibilities of Happay and the client during setup.

·        Definitions of all required fields.

·        API structure for container creation and updates.

·        Field formats and payload examples.

·        Troubleshooting and FAQs.

This SOP is applicable to enterprise clients using project-based employee allocation and who require project metadata integrated into the Happay platform.

Definitions

GA Container: A GA (Global Assignment) container is a project-specific logical entity used in Happay to represent employee allocation, with defined parameters such as task, project number, assignment period, and location.

Container Type: Indicates the nature of the container. For project assignments, this value is always "Project".

Metafields: Metafields are the custom data values defined by the client to capture project-specific information inside a container. They are configured as key-value pairs.

Native Fields: These are standard fields required by the API structure such as user_id, container_type, container_id, product_name, and requestId.

Container ID: A unique identifier for each project container. It typically corresponds to the PROJECT_NUMBER.

User ID: The unique identifier of the user in Happay who is being assigned to the container.

Responsibilities Breakdown

Happays Responsibility

·        Enabling GA container APIs in the clients environment.

·        Providing sandbox access and validating API payload structure.

·        Mapping the metafields for backend workflows and downstream logic.

·        Providing support for container errors, field conflicts, and versioning issues.

Clients Responsibility

·        Generating valid payloads for container creation and updates.

·        Ensuring all required native and metafields are included.

·        Maintaining proper field naming and date formats (YYYY-MM-DD).

·        Using correct user_id and PROJECT_NUMBER values.

·        Avoiding duplication and ensuring updates happen via PUT, not POST.

Integration Details

Ø  Base URL

All API requests are made to the following endpoint:

https://api-v2.happay.in/auth/v1/runtime-containers/bulk/

Ø  Native Fields Required

These are mandatory fields at the container level and must be included in every request:

·        user_id  ID of the employee in Happay.

·        requestId  A custom string to help track requests (e.g., "Project_Create").

·        container_type  Must be "Project" for GA containers.

·        product_name  Set to "Project".

·        container_id  (Only for updates). This must match the PROJECT_NUMBER.

Ø  Metafields Required

The following metafields are required for each container to successfully represent an assignment:

·        EMPLOYEE_ID  Internal employee code.

·        PROJECT_NUMBER  Unique project identifier (same as container_id).

·        PROJECT_NAME  Full project name.

·        PROJECT_START_DATE  Start date of the project (format: YYYY-MM-DD).

·        PROJECT_END_DATE  End date of the project (format: YYYY-MM-DD).

·        EMPLOYEE_NAME  Name of the employee assigned.

·        EMPLOYEE_ASSIGNMENT_START_DATE  Assignment start date for the employee.

·        EMPLOYEE_ASSIGNMENT_END_DATE  Assignment end date for the employee.

·        LOCATION_ENTITY  Location of the assignment or project.

·        TASK_NUMBER  Internal task code or identifier.

·        TASK_NAME  Description of the assigned task.

Note: All metafield names are case-sensitive. Any mismatch in naming may result in errors or silent rejection.

FAQs

1. Why do I get a container_id missing error during update?
You likely used the PUT method without passing the container_id. Make sure to include container_id and that it matches an existing PROJECT_NUMBER.

2. Is the PROJECT_NUMBER field case-sensitive?
Yes. It must exactly match the previously submitted value when using it as container_id in updates.

3. Can an employee have multiple project containers?
Yes. As long as each container has a unique PROJECT_NUMBER.

4. What format should I use for dates?
Always use YYYY-MM-DD format for all date fields.

5. ssssWhat should I do if the request returns User ID not found?
Ensure the employee is first created in Happay and the correct user_id is being used in the API request.
